ny aspects DaoC is better than EQ, and in many aspects it's worse.  I guess weather or not you enjoy one more than the other all depends on what kind of problems you can deal with more than others.  For instance, DaoC hasn't a whole lot of high end game, other than RvR, which can be very fun and rewarding (if that's your kind of thing).  On the other hand, it doesn't have the problems of finding groups (since everybody can solo) nor are the graphics as blocky as EQ.  DaoC is much faster paced, and recovery time is much quicker also.  There are alot of different aspects to compare, so really it's kind of like trading one set of problem for another.  It all depends on what you consider to be an intolerable problem, and what you consider to be to be tolerable.  I, for one, consider the (imo, few problems) that DaoC has to be nothing more than mere annoyances and nothing that would seriously make me consider quitting the game.  One aspect that I really like is that the greediness of EQ doesn't exist in DaoC.  The politics of &quot;who earned what item in which raid&quot; doesn't exist.  The graphics are better (by far, even when compared to Luclin).  The loading times are faster, and smoother.  Group finding is considerably easier.  The ability to solo is there.  The game doesn't revolve around monetary value.  Inflation does not exist.  The &quot;you have to be in an uber guild to do anything&quot; problem isn't there.  There are no raid calendars.  You don't have to pay insane amount of money to get from one place to the other (porting).  The comparisons are endless, but these that I've listed are just the ones that used to really annoy me to no end on Everquest.  I'm not going to sit here and say that EQ is a crappy game, cause that's not true.  Eq is a great game, but, for me it was just time to find something different and something with an alternate direction other than personal wealth in money and items.  In doing that I sacrificed the EQ high end game (Raids, etc...), but for me that was a sacrifice that I was willing to make.  The high end game of EQ was never that important to me so I didn't lose anything in that aspect.<br><br>  Try it out, get to about 20-30 and see what you think?  That is the best way to figure out if you like it better or not.  You can always go back and play EQ again.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    Hope that helped out a little.<br><br>P.S.  I would have used ICQ, but I don't have it loaded nor do I know how it works.<br><br>-Nick <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ushandael.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Shandael</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/19/02 6:48:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus95980frm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=203.topic&index=3>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re</span><hr size=1> I agree with Siryah on all of his points (although I haven't experienced the high-lvl game yet).<br><br>Some people prefer EQ and others DAoC. That's all fine. I play both, but I find myself playing DAoC more and more.<br>The reasons for me are thus;<br><br>1) The Roleplaying Servers have a definite well-known historical reference (at least with Albion) that really sets it apart from EQ's RP, and adds a very rich, fertile ground for true fans of the Arthurian legends, of which I'm one.<br><br>2) I rather enjoy the absence of zone-wide spam onslaughts which detract from the game. To me it's more realistic; crowd chatter in towns, but outside only the chatter of passer-by's or groupmates. <br><br>3) No more horrid downtimes. I *really* like that!<br><br>4) No more horrid death penalties that takes weeks to recover from.<br><br>5) A very nicely done trade skill system. No more fighting for time at forges or other immovable crafting objects. Multi-level crafting either seperately or all-encompassing. Player made items that are actually worth something at every level! Salvaging items for tradeskill components.<br><br>6) Casters who are actually worth something!<br><br>7) Archery that is more than just a joke.<br><br><!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  No cookie-cutter classes. Specialize your character the way you want to play them.<br><br>9) Better AI. Mobs circle, call for help when badly wounded, some run for help at the slightest glimpse of you, attack different areas of your body, weapons are actually more effective/less effective against certain types.<br><br>10) Random quests, commission work, 2-hour tasks.<br><br>11) Automatic loot dispersal in groups, no ninja-looting.<br><br>The list goes on. I enjoy DAoC. They took a lot of things that were problematic with other games and made them work with an emphasis on letting the players have a good time...and isn't that what it's all about?<br><br>It just seems to me, the more and more I play the two, that EQ tries to hold players back, whereas DAoC wants us to get out there and have some fun.<br> <p><img src=http://members.aol.com/angshan/Sapp1.jpg><BR> Remembrances of past glories<BR>Is the fire of future endeavors.</p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus95980frm17.showPrevMessage?topicID=203.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus